This paper is primarily focused on computer vision (CV) and specifically on the problem of crowd counting. Therefore, cs.CV is the most likely sub-category. The paper proposes a novel approach that involves using a dedicated network branch to predict the object/non-object mask, which could be seen as an artificial intelligence (AI) problem. Hence, cs.AI is also a likely sub-category. The paper also involves extensive experimentation and analysis to identify the most effective solution, which could be seen as a machine learning (ML) problem. Therefore, cs.LG is another likely sub-category. The paper also deals with video frames, which could be seen as a multimedia (MM) problem. Hence, cs.MM is also a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of neural networks, which could be seen as a neural and evolutionary computing (NE) problem. Hence, cs.NE is also a likely sub-category.
